= Install a small slackware =
 * Require: tar-1.13, installpkg
 * installpkg --root /slack2 /jick/slackware/slackware/*.tgz
 * chroot /slack2 /sbin/ldconfig
 * chroot /slack2

= Basical packages =
 * aaa_base
 * aaa_elflibs
 * sysvinit
 * devs

= X11 server packages =
 * l/freetype	- A Free, High-Quality, and Portable Font Engine
 * x/fontconfig	- Font library and tools
 * x/x11		- X11 base package
 * x/x11-devel	- Libraries and other files for X programming
 * x/x11-doc	- text documentation for X
 * x/x11-fonts-misc - a minimal set of fonts needed to run X
 * x/x11-fonts-scale - Speedo, Type 1, and TrueType scalable fonts for X
 * xap/fvwm		- a small and fast virtual window manager for X
 *
 * x/dejavu-ttf	- based on the Bitstream Vera Fonts, purpose is to provide a
   wider range of characters
 * x/x11-doc-html - HTML documentation for X
 * x/x11-xdmx	- Distributed Multi-head X server
 * x/x11-xnest	- a nested X server
 * x/x11-xvfb	- virtual framebuffer X server

= Slackware Boot process (11.0) =
 * (kernel) -> /sbin/init
 * -> /etc/inittab
 * --> /etc/rc.d/rc.S
   * ---> Mount /proc right away.
   * ---> If 'nohotplug' was given at boot, or rc.hotplug has been turned off
     (add a 2.4.x kernel is running), then shut off hotplugging in the kernel
     now.
   * ---> Start devfsd if necessary. On newer kernels, udev should be used
     instead. (rc.devfsd)
   * ---> Mount sysfs next, if the kernel supports it.
   * ---> Enable swapping.
   * ---> Test to see if the root partition is read-only, like it ought to be.
   * ---> See if a forced filesystem check was requested at shutdown.
   * ---> Check the root filesystem.
   * ---> Delete any old /etc/mtab here.
   * ---> Remounting the / partition will initialize the new /etc/mtab.
   * ---> Fix /etc/mtab to list sys and proc if they ware not yet entered in
     /etc/mtab because / was still mounted read-only.
   * ---> Initialize udev to manage /dev entries and hotplugging for 2.6.x
     kernels. (rc.udev)
   * ---> Set the system time from the hardware clock using hwclock --hctosys
   * ---> Configure ISA Plug-and-Play devices.
   * ---> Load any kernel modules that are needed. (rc.modules.local,
     rc.modules-$FULL_KERNEL_VERSION, rc.modules)
   * ---> Configure runtime kernel parameters. (sysctl)
   * ---> Initialize the LVM.
   * ---> Check all the non-root filesystems.
   * ---> Mount usbfs if we're not using hotplug.
   * ---> Mount non-root fs in fstab, but not NFS or SMB because TCP/IP is not
     yet configured, and not proc or sysfs bacause those have already been
     mounted.
   * ---> Enable swapping again, for maybe a swapfile.
   * ---> Clean up some temporary files.
   * ---> Create /tmp/{.ICE-unix,.X11-unix} if they are not present.
   * ---> Attempt to umount and remove any leftover /initrd.
   * ---> Create a fresh utmp file.
   * ---> Update any files added in DOS.
   * ---> Setup the /etc/motd to reflect the current kernel level.
   * ---> If there are SystemV init scripts for this runlevel, run them.
     (rc.sysinit)
   * ---> Run serial ports setup scripts. (rc.serial)
   * ---> Carry an entropy pool between reboots to improve randomness.
 * --> /etc/rc.d/rc.M
  * ---> Screen blacks after 15ms idle time, and powers down in 1 hour if the
    kernel supports APM or ACPI power management. (setterm)
  * ---> Set the hostname.
  * ---> Save the contents of 'dmesg'.
  * ---> If we are returning from single-user mode we will need to restart
    udevd on systems that use udev. (rc.udev)
  * ---> Start the system logger. (rc.syslog)
  * ---> Initialize PCMCIA devices. (rc.pcmcia)
  * ---> Initialize the networking hardware. (rc.inet1)
	* ----> Get the configuration information from /etc/rc.d/rc.inet1.conf.
	* ----> Compose a list of interfaces from rc.inet1.conf.
	* ----> Functions: {lo,if,gateway}_{up,down}(), start(), stop().
  * ---> Initialize the hotplugging subsystem. (rc.hotplug)
  * ---> Look for additional USB/SCSI/IEEE1294/etc devices on multiple LUNs.
    (rc.scanluns)
  * ---> Start networking daemons. (rc.inet2)
	* ----> Mount remote (NFS) filesystems. (rc.portmap)
	* ----> Mount remove (SMB) filesystems.
	* ----> Start the system logger if it is not already running (maybe
	  bacause /usr is on a network partition). (rc.syslog)
	* ----> If there is a firewall script, run it before enabling packet
	  forwarding. (rc.firewall)
	* ----> Turn on IPv4 packet forwarding support. (rc.ip_forward)
	* ----> Start the inetd server. (rc.inetd)
	* ----> Start the OpenSSH SSH daemon. (rc.sshd)
	* ----> Start the BIND name server daemon. (rc.bind)
	* ----> Start NIS. (rc.yp)
	* ----> Start the NFS server. (rc.nfsd)
	* ----> Start the network routing daemon. (rc.routed)
	* ----> Start the system status server. (rwhod)
	* ----> Fire up the PC-NFS daemon(s). (rc.pcnfsd)
  * ---> Remove stale locks and junk files.
  * ---> Remove stale hunt sockets so the game can start.
  * ---> Ensure basic filesystem permissions sanity.
  * ---> Update all the shared library links. (ldconfig)
  * ---> Update the X font indexes. (fc-cache)
  * ---> Start dnsmasq, a simple DHCP/DNS server. (rc.dnsmasq)
  * ---> Start the print spooling system. (rc.cups, rc.hplip, rc.lprng)
  * ---> Start netatalk. (rc.atalk)
  * ---> Start smartd. (rc.smartd)
  * ---> If we're using udev, make /dev/cdrom and any other optical drive
    symlinks if some udev rule hasn't made them already.
  * ---> Monitor the UPS with genpowerd.
  * ---> Turn on process accounting. (pacct)
  * ---> Start crond (Dillon's crond). 
  * ---> Start atd (manages jobs scheduled with 'at').
  * ---> Check quotas and then turn quota system on.
  * ---> Start the SASL authentication server. (rc.saslauthd)
  * ---> Start the sendmail daemon. (rc.sendmail)
  * ---> Start APM or ACPI daemon. (apmd, rc.acpid)
  * ---> Load ALSA (sound) defaults. (rc.alsa)
  * ---> Load a custom screen font. (rc.font)
  * ---> Load a custom keymap. (rc.keymap)
  * ---> Start the MySQL database. (rc.mysqld)
  * ---> Start Apache web server. (rc.httpd)
  * ---> Start OpenLDAP. (rc.openldap)
  * ---> Start Samba. (rc.samba)
  * ---> Start the GPM mouse server. (rc.gpm)
  * ---> If there are SystemV init scripts fro this runlevel, run them.
    (rc.sysvinit)
  * ---> Start the local setup procedure. (rc.local)

= misc =
 * xwmconfig - switch window manager
 * reliable > speed
 * xdpyinfo - display info utility for X

